<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-352-140  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 352 140.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  April 16 1990 v7 n15 p1(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Merger of Raxco, UIS to create largest vendor of VMS systemutilities.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Patch, Kimberly.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Raxco Inc and UIS Inc, two of the largest VAX/VMX system softwarepublishers, announce a merger agreement whereby the two companieswill become the largest third-party supplier of VMS systemutilities in the DEC market.andP;  Both companies signed a letter ofintent in Apr 1990 and the merger is expected to be complete byJul 1990.andP;  According to a Raxco spokesperson, the companies wantedto combine product lines to increase market strength in Europe.andO;The merger also occurs while DEC is working with ComputerAssociates to develop VMS system utilities.andP;  Raxco and UIS areexpected to capitalize on trends toward the increased need forsophisticated system management tools in business.andP;  When the twocompanies merge, they will create a new company name based on acombination of both companies' names.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Raxco Software Inc. (acquisitions and mergers)UIS Inc. (acquisitions and mergers).andO;Topic:     MergerManagementMarketing StrategySystems SoftwareThird-Party VendorsSoftware Publishers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Merger of Raxco, UIS to create largest vendor of VMS system utilitiesandM;Two of the largest players in the VAX/VMS system software arena will announcethis week a merger agreement under which the two companies will become thelargest third-party supplier of VMS system utilities in the DEC market.andM;Raxco of Rockville, Md., and UIS of Great Britain have signed a letter ofintent to combine operations.andP;  The merger is expected to be complete within90 days, according to John Becker, Raxco's chief financial officer and vicepresident of finance.andM;&quot;We [wanted] to combine product lines [to] increase our strength in Europe toprepare for 1992, [and] we [wanted] to achieve mass--to become a bigcompany,&quot; Becker said.andM;&quot;We've got a complementary range of products--Raxco has performancemanagement; we have system management and data center management,&quot; said AlanDiggory, UIS marketing manager for Europe.andM;&quot;What we're doing is gearing ourselves up for the competitiveness of themarket to come,&quot; Diggory said.andM;The timing of the merger is also key, according to the two companies andothers in the industry.andM;DEC is currently working with Computer Associates of Garden City, N.Y., todevelop a broad range of VMS system utilities that will mirror the functionsof tools that Computer Associates currently provides for IBM mainframeenvironments.andM;IBM's system management offerings and its third-party tools have greaterdepth than DEC's, but now that DEC is moving into the commercial arena, DECmust watch its large computers, said Doug Crook, a senior analyst atDataquest, a market research company in San Jose, Calif.andM;&quot;Business managers are spending [millions of] dollars and literally bettingtheir business on these decisions.andP;  [A mainframe is] a very expensive asset,and they need the most out of it.andP;  That's where you come into systemmanagement tools,&quot; Crook said.andM;&quot;Digital is still struggling with that.andP;  It's something they have to do ifthey want to sell their high-end systems into the commercial marketplace,&quot; headded.andM;Raxco and UIS &quot;don't want to miss out on this window of opportunity, [and]there's probably some fear about the Computer Associates agreement,&quot; he said.andM;&quot;DEC has repeatedly voiced an intent to do something [about its systemmanagement weaknesses], &quot;Raxco's Becker said.andP;  &quot;If DEC and ComputerAssociates do start rolling system management tools out the door, we want tobe there too,&quot; Becker said.andM;The merger was engineered largely by Eddie Gloyne, former CEO at UIS,officials from both companies said.andM;UIS' Diggory said regarding the name of the new venture, &quot;We will not useUIS, we will not use Raxco, and [the new name] will not be a combination ofthe names.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>